    # TH (Tyrosine Hydroxylase) — Expert Analysis
    ## Biological function
    TH catalyzes the rate-limiting step in catecholamine biosynthesis: hydroxylation of L-tyrosine to L-DOPA, using tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4), molecular oxygen, and ferrous iron as cofactors. The 497-aa canonical protein is a homotetramer with three functional domains — an N-terminal regulatory domain (Ser19/Ser31/Ser40 phosphorylation sites controlled by PKA, CaMKII, ERK1/2, and PKC), a central catalytic domain housing the iron-binding active site, and a C-terminal tetramerization domain. TH is expressed in dopaminergic, noradrenergic, and adrenergic neurons of the substantia nigra, locus coeruleus, ventral tegmental area, and adrenal medulla chromaffin cells. The unusually high GC content (65.3%) and compact 8 kb locus on 11p15.5 sit within an imprinted region adjacent to INS and IGF2 — relevant for allele-specific expression analyses. The 14 transcripts (8 protein-coding) reflect alternative splicing in exon 2 producing human-specific isoforms (hTH1–hTH4) with differential N-terminal regulatory properties; rodents express only the hTH1 equivalent, which has direct implications for translational modeling.
    ## Key variants and disease associations
    Biallelic loss-of-function or hypomorphic TH variants cause **DOPA-responsive dystonia / infantile parkinsonism (Segawa syndrome type B, OMIM #605407)** — an autosomal recessive disorder spanning a phenotypic continuum from mild L-DOPA-responsive dystonia to severe neonatal encephalopathy with autonomic crises. The recurrent **p.Arg233His** and **p.Leu236Pro** missense variants destabilize the catalytic domain; **c.-71C>T** in the cAMP-response element disrupts promoter activity and produces the milder Segawa phenotype. CSF shows reduced HVA and MHPG with normal 5-HIAA — a diagnostic signature distinguishing TH deficiency from aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase deficiency. Beyond monogenic disease, TH is the cardinal molecular marker of the dopaminergic neurons selectively lost in **Parkinson's disease**; striatal TH immunoreactivity and nigral TH+ cell counts are the standard quantitative endpoints in PD models. TH is also implicated in **pheochromocytoma/paraganglioma** biology (catecholamine output), **neuroblastoma** staging (TH mRNA as a minimal residual disease marker in bone marrow and peripheral blood), and as a susceptibility locus in schizophrenia and bipolar disorder GWAS.
    ## Regulation and pharmacology
    TH activity is gated by end-product feedback inhibition — dopamine and norepinephrine bind the regulatory domain and compete with BH4. Phosphorylation at Ser40 by PKA relieves this inhibition and is the dominant short-term activation mechanism in vivo; Ser31 phosphorylation by ERK1/2 increases Vmax. Chronic regulation occurs via CREB-mediated transcription downstream of cAMP and depolarization. **α-Methyl-para-tyrosine (metyrosine, Demser)** is the clinically used competitive TH inhibitor for pheochromocytoma preoperative management. The enzyme is highly sensitive to oxidative stress — iron-catalyzed Fenton chemistry at the active site contributes to its selective vulnerability in PD, and α-synuclein binds and inhibits TH directly, linking SNCA pathology to dopamine depletion mechanistically.
    ## Experimental recommendations
    For **functional characterization**, use SH-SY5Y or LUHMES cells (endogenous TH expression, inducible dopaminergic differentiation) or iPSC-derived midbrain dopaminergic neurons (FOXA2+/LMX1A+/TH+) for patient-specific variants. Quantify TH by Western blot with phospho-specific antibodies (pSer19/31/40), and measure enzymatic activity via HPLC-ECD detection of L-DOPA from tyrosine substrate. For **variant interpretation**, express recombinant TH in E. coli BL21, purify by Ni-NTA + size-exclusion, and assay kinetics (Km for tyrosine and BH4, Vmax, BH4 cooperativity) — published WT values give Km(Tyr) ≈ 25 μM, Km(BH4) ≈ 30 μM. Thermal shift assays (DSF) detect destabilizing missense variants efficiently. For **in vivo work**, the TH-Cre mouse (Jackson #008601) remains the workhorse for dopaminergic circuit dissection; MitoPark (DAT-Cre × Tfam-flox) and 6-OHDA lesion models recapitulate progressive TH+ neuron loss. For **disease modeling**, prioritize iPSC-derived mDA neurons from TH-deficiency patients with parallel CRISPR-corrected isogenic controls — quantify L-DOPA rescue dose-response as the primary functional readout. For **clinical translation in PD**, monitor striatal TH via [18F]-DOPA PET or DAT-SPECT as surrogate biomarkers.

